217 // classes derived from base:
218 
219 class integer; // derived from base
220  // self contains the integer value as a C (long)integer (INT)
221 
222 class longinteger; // derived from base
223  // self is a pointer to LONGINTEGER_REPRESENTATION
224  // which contains the sign, the length
225  // and a C array of chars containing
226  // the decimal representation of the signless longinteger value
227 
228 class matrix; // derived from base
229  // self is a pointer obtained from
230  // calloc_m_times_n_objects().
231  // this means that we have an array of m * n + 2 objacts,
232  // self points to the m * n array of user entries
233  // and at offset [-2] we have m (as an integer object),
234  // at offset [-1] we have n (as an integer object).
235  // matrix access (via s_ij or via operator[])
236  // is range checked.
237 
238 class bitmatrix; // derived from base
239  // self is a pointer to BITMATRIX_REPRESENTATION
240  // which contains integers m, n, N and an array p of UINT4s
241  // holding the bits in a row by row fashion.
242 
243 class Vector; // derived from base
244  // self is a pointer obtained from
245  // calloc_nobjects_plus_length().
246  // this means that we have an array of n + 1 objacts,
247  // self points to the n array of user entries
248  // and at offset [-1] we have the length l (as an integer object),
249  // vector access (via s_i or via operator[])
250  // is range checked.
251 
252 class memory; // derived from base
253  // self is a pointer to char which has some additional
254  // information stored at offset -3, -2, -1 in INT4s.
255  // these are alloc_length, used_length and cur_pointer.
256 
257 class hollerith; // derived from base
258 // there are so many string classes around so that I call
259 // my string class hollerith class!
260 // n.b.: Herman Hollerith (Buffalo 1860 - Washington 1929),
261 // American engeneer; he invented
262 // statistical machines working with perforated cards
263 // In 1896, he founded the Tabulating Machine Corporation
264 // which later became IBM.
265 
266 
267 // classes derived from vector:
268 
269  class permutation; // derived from vector
270  // a vector holding the images of the
271  // points 0, 1, ..., l-1 under the permutation.
272  // Note that the images are in 0, 1, ... , l-1 again!
273  // the length is already stored in the vector.
274 
275  class number_partition; // derived from vector
276  // a vector of length 2:
277  // offset 0: the type (PARTITION_TYPE_VECTOR
278  // or PARTITION_TYPE_EXPONENT)
279  // offset 1: the self part holding the parts
